\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Cost of Effort
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Effort-Cost"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The profit for employer and workers are given by; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{Employer Profits}=(v-w)e\label{eq:employer-profit}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{Worker Earnings}=w-c-c(e)\label{eq:worker-profit}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use 
\begin_inset Formula $v=120,$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c=20$
\end_inset

.
 The choice of payoff functions (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:employer-profit"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:worker-profit"

\end_inset

) and parameters (
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

) is made following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Fehr1998"

\end_inset

.
 To ensure that payoffs are always positive and to avoid concerns about
 expectations of loss aversion 
\begin_inset Formula $w\in\{20,35,40,...,120\}.$
\end_inset

 As mentioned earlier, subjects will play this game for 10 periods, one
 of those 10 periods will be randomly selected and the payment to the subject
 will be determined on the basis of payoff in that period.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To avoid reputation effects, a worker in each period will be told that it
 is partnered with a new employer i.e.
 a worker will be told that it will never be matched with the same employer
 again.
 Worker will also be told that the game will proceed anonymously i.e.
 employer will never observe the identity of a worker.
 In the absence of social preference, a worker should always choose minimum
 effort (
\begin_inset Formula $e_{min}$
\end_inset

) irrespective of the wage offer.
 As once the wage is determined there is no pecuniary incentive to choose
 
\begin_inset Formula $e>e_{min}.$
\end_inset

 In this experiment we are only interested in the worker's problem, therefore
 there will be no real employers and wages by the employers will be randomly
 determined.
 Random wages are introduced to give more control on the experiment and
 to avoid any confounds from employer choice that may influence worker's
 effort choice.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While we agree that deception should be discouraged in labortary experiments,
 our experiment does not violate any of the ethical concerns associated
 with deception.
 We were careful to follow APA guidelines for deception.
 There appear to be three concerns at stake regardign deception.
 First, there is the argument that deception will harm the subjects.
 This argument is not relevant in this case because we don't see how subjects
 can be harmed by the deception in this case.
 The earnings of the subjects are not affected because of this deception
 as compared to having real people playing the game.
 Second, there is the argument that deception will 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

poison
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the subject pool for future experiments.
 We avoid this problem by not debriefing the subjects about this deception.
 Debriefing the subjects can broadcast the deception to other potential
 subjects and hence potentially affect their behavior in future experiments.
 Third, the suspicion of deception may bias the results of the experiment.
 If such a bias exist it will bias the results in the direction of null
 effect.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Race Salient Treatment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This treatment will be same as baseline treatment except that when workers
 see the wage offer, they will see the picture of an employer who made the
 wage offer.
 We use neurtal pictures of Blacks and Whites from the Chicago Face Database
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
citep{Ma2015}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Chicago Face Database (CFD) is a free resource consisting of 158 high-resolutio
n, standardized photographs of Black and White males and females between
 the ages of 18 and 40 years.
 These photographs are rated on a number of different psychological dimensions
 (e.g.
 attractiveness and trustworthiness).
 Using pictures from CFD (compared to using pictures of real people) offer
 us the better experimental control and is also cost-effective.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Race-Salient-Layout"

\end_inset

 presents the layout of interface that the worker will see while making
 the effort choice.
 Each worker will see 5 White and 5 Black pictures in the random order.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(How does within group behavior changes will effect the reciprocity, e.g.
 white faces might be attractive to both blacks and whites.
 )
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Layout Race Salient.png
	scale 70

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Layout of the Race Salient Treatment
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Race-Salient-Layout"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Three Stage Treatment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Three stage treatment will be same as Baseline except that there will be
 an additional stage to the game.
 We closely follow the design in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Fehr1997"

\end_inset

 to formulate this third stage.
 Workers will be told that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

In the third stage employer will observe your effort choice and decide whether
 to reward or punish you.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 So after the effort is chosen, employer will observe the effort choice
 and choose a number 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in[0,2]$
\end_inset

.
 The workers earning from previous two stages will then be multiplied by
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Both 
\begin_inset Formula $p<1$
\end_inset

 (a punishment) and 
\begin_inset Formula $p>1$
\end_inset

 (a reward) will be costly to employers with cost schedule as given in Table
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "reciprocity-cost"

\end_inset

.
 The payoff functions in this treatment will be as follows; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{Employer Profits}=(v-w)e-k(p)\label{eq:employer-profit-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{Worker Earnings}=[w-c-c(e)]p\label{eq:worker-profit-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

